{"title_page": "Prostitution in Bolivia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n'''Prostitution in Bolivia''' is legal and [[Regulated prostitution|regulated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html|title=WORLD BRIEFING - THE AMERICAS; Bolivia: Prostitutes Sew Lips Together In Protest|last=Reuters|date=25 October 2007|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zSyJAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=CultureShock! Bolivia: A Survival Guide to Customs and Etiquette|first=Mark|last=Cramer|date=15 November 2009|publisher=Marshall Cavendish International Asia Pte Ltd|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9789814484350}}</ref> It is only permitted by registered [[prostitute]]s in licensed [[brothel]]s.<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=24 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> Prostitutes must register and must undergo regular health checks for sexually transmitted diseases (every 20 days). The police are allowed to check whether the prostitutes are registered or not, and have attended a clinic during the previous 20 days.<ref name=\"spl\" /> \n\nIn 2016 [[UNAIDS]] estimated there were 30,523 prostitutes in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Societal views==\nAlthough prostitution is widespread in Bolivia, the prostitutes are severely stigmatized by society, they are blamed for everything from broken homes to the rising [[HIV]]-infection rate.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cPG9F7fTTLIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=Forced Labor: The Prostitution of Children: Symposium Proceedings|first1=Maureen|last1=Jaffe|first2=Sonia|last2=Rosen|date=1 July 1997|publisher=DIANE Publishing|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780788146060}}</ref> In 2007, in [[El Alto]], hundreds of prostitutes were attacked, forced to strip and beaten by angry locals; several brothels were burnt. Citizens demanded that brothels and bars be located at least 3,200 feet away from schools.  The municipal government responded by closing all brothels within 1,600 feet of schools, but took no action against those who had attacked the prostitutes. \"We are Bolivia's unloved,\" said Yuly Perez, vice-president of [[:es:Onaem|ONAEM]], the Bolivian sex workers' union, \"If we don't work, who's going to feed our kids?\" Another representative from the sex worker organization said that: \"People think the point of our organization is to expand prostitution in Bolivia. In fact, we want the opposite. Our ideal world is one free of the economic desperation that forces women into this business.\"<ref>Friedman, Jean. (24 October 2007) [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1675348,00.html Prostitutes Strike in Bolivia]. TIME. Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref>\n\n==Child prostitution==\n\nIn Bolivia, the average age of entry into prostitution is 16.<ref name=\"unhcr1\">[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,OMCT,,BOL,46c190cc0,0.html Refworld | Rights of the Child in Bolivia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009083259/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,OMCT,,BOL,46c190cc0,0.html |date=9 October 2012 }}. UNHCR (31 January 2005). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> [[Child prostitution]] is a serious problem, particularly in urban areas and in the [[Chapare province|Chapare]] region.<ref name=\"state1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175721/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119149.htm 2008 Human Rights Report: Bolivia]. State.gov (25 February 2009). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> \nMost children [[forced into prostitution]] come from the lower social classes and from broken families. Only 12.6% of these children have any education, leaving them with few opportunities. As a result, many remain in the sex trade throughout adulthood, despite wanting to exit. Approximately one third of girls and adolescents in prostitution have between one and five children, mostly under the age of 5.<ref name=\"unhcr1\"/>\nMost child prostitutes work on the streets, inside brothels or inside bars and clubs. \n\nThere are different types of child prostitution, varying with the economic power of the client and the age of the child. Upper-class clients tend to seek older adolescents aged 16\u201317 (and young adult prostitutes aged 18\u201320). Many of these youth come from Eastern Bolivia and from outside of the country. This type of prostitution is organised by closed networks, and is subject to very few controls. In some cases, the sexual contact between these adolescents and their clients takes place at the client's house. Adolescents from all parts of the country prostitute themselves in local bars or pubs, mainly for middle-class clients. [[Street prostitution]] involves women and girls of all ages who typically enter the trade when they are between the ages of 12 and 15 years. Finally, there is a form of \u201chidden\u201d prostitution, which can involve children as young as 8 years, often in exchange for drugs or some kind of treat or toy. During the day, these children stay in the street often working as street vendors, domestic servants or waitresses. At night they go to dance clubs or sell alcohol in the street. Clients of this type of prostitution are generally adults or adolescents with little money.<ref name=\"unhcr1\"/> \n\nThe problem of child prostitution is exacerbated by poorly enforced laws and by rare and ineffective police raids. However, recently, more efforts have been done to address this problem; in 2008, the police raided several [[brothels]] and rescued  215 children who were working there.<ref name=\"state2\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090621101815/http://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2009/123135.htm Trafficking in Persons Report 2009 Country Narratives \u2013 Countries A Through C]. State.gov. Retrieved on 30 March 2011.</ref> \nThe International Organization for Migration (IOM) and the NGOs Save the Children and Pro-Adolescente conducted public awareness campaigns on the [[trafficking of children]]. La Paz Department and the La Paz city government each operate a shelter for abused and exploited children.\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Bolivia}}\nEconomic and social problems create a climate which is favorable to [[human trafficking]]. Young Bolivian women and girls are trafficked from rural to urban areas for commercial sexual exploitation;<ref name=\"state2\"/> women and children from the indigenous ethnic groups in the [[Altiplano]] region are at greater risk of being [[human trafficking|trafficked]] into prostitution.<ref name=\"state1\"/>\nFaced with extreme poverty, many citizens become economic migrants, and some are victimized by traffickers and forced into prostitution, both inside and outside Bolivia. \n \nThe country is also a source for victims trafficked for sexual exploitation to [[Argentina]], [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Spain]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VG2mDHVSUDcC&pg=PA250&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=Bolivia Company Laws and Regulations Handbook|first=Usa International Business|last=Publications|date=3 March 2008|publisher=Int'l Business Publications|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9781433069512}}</ref> Weak controls along the borders exacerbate this problem.<ref name=\"state1\"/>\n\nIn 2018 the [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] downgraded Bolivia's rank from 'Tier 2 Watch List' to a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 3]]' country.<ref name=\"state18\">{{cite web |title=Bolivia 2018 Trafficking in Persons Report |url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282616.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234113/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282616.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 July 2018 |website=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=26 July 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gvnet.com/childprostitution/Bolivia.htm Child Prostitution:The Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children]\n\n{{South America in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution by country|Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Bolivian society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in South America|Bolivia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n'''Prostitution in Bolivia''' is legal and [[Regulated prostitution|regulated]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html|title=WORLD BRIEFING - THE AMERICAS; Bolivia: Prostitutes Sew Lips Together In Protest|last=Reuters|date=25 October 2007|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zSyJAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA71&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=CultureShock! Bolivia: A Survival Guide to Customs and Etiquette|first=Mark|last=Cramer|date=15 November 2009|publisher=Marshall Cavendish International Asia Pte Ltd|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9789814484350}}</ref> It is only permitted by registered [[prostitute]]s in licensed [[brothel]]s.<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=24 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> Prostitutes must register and must undergo regular health checks for sexually transmitted diseases (every 20 days). The police are allowed to check whether the prostitutes are registered or not, and have attended a clinic during the previous 20 days.<ref name=\"spl\" /> \n\nIn 2016 [[UNAIDS]] estimated there were 30,523 prostitutes in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Societal views==\nAlthough prostitution is widespread in Bolivia, the prostitutes are severely stigmatized by society, they are blamed for everything from broken homes to the rising [[HIV]]-infection rate.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=cPG9F7fTTLIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=Forced Labor: The Prostitution of Children: Symposium Proceedings|first1=Maureen|last1=Jaffe|first2=Sonia|last2=Rosen|date=1 July 1997|publisher=DIANE Publishing|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780788146060}}</ref> In 2007, in [[El Alto]], hundreds of prostitutes were attacked, forced to strip and beaten by angry locals; several brothels were burnt. Citizens demanded that brothels and bars be located at least 3,200 feet away from schools.  The municipal government responded by closing all brothels within 1,600 feet of schools, but took no action against those who had attacked the prostitutes. \"We are Bolivia's unloved,\" said Yuly Perez, vice-president of [[:es:Onaem|ONAEM]], the Bolivian sex workers' union, \"If we don't work, who's going to feed our kids?\" Another representative from the sex worker organization said that: \"People think the point of our organization is to expand prostitution in Bolivia. In fact, we want the opposite. Our ideal world is one free of the economic desperation that forces women into this business.\"<ref>Friedman, Jean. (24 October 2007) [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1675348,00.html Prostitutes Strike in Bolivia]. TIME. Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref>\n\n==Child prostitution==\n\nIn Bolivia, the average age of entry into prostitution is 16.<ref name=\"unhcr1\">[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,OMCT,,BOL,46c190cc0,0.html Refworld | Rights of the Child in Bolivia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009083259/http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/publisher,OMCT,,BOL,46c190cc0,0.html |date=9 October 2012 }}. UNHCR (31 January 2005). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> [[Child prostitution]] is a serious problem, particularly in urban areas and in the [[Chapare province|Chapare]] region.<ref name=\"state1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175721/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/wha/119149.htm 2008 Human Rights Report: Bolivia]. State.gov (25 February 2009). Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> \nMost children [[forced into prostitution]] come from the lower social classes and from broken families. Only 12.6% of these children have any education, leaving them with few opportunities. As a result, many remain in the sex trade throughout adulthood, despite wanting to exit. Approximately one third of girls and adolescents in prostitution have between one and five children, mostly under the age of 5.<ref name=\"unhcr1\"/>\nMost child prostitutes work on the streets, inside brothels or inside bars and clubs. \n\nThere are different types of child prostitution, varying with the economic power of the client and the age of the child. Upper-class clients tend to seek older adolescents aged 16\u201317 (and young adult prostitutes aged 18\u201320). Many of these youth come from Eastern Bolivia and from outside of the country. This type of prostitution is organised by closed networks, and is subject to very few controls. In some cases, the sexual contact between these adolescents and their clients takes place at the client\u2019s house. Adolescents from all parts of the country prostitute themselves in local bars or pubs, mainly for middle-class clients. [[Street prostitution]] involves women and girls of all ages who typically enter the trade when they are between the ages of 12 and 15 years. Finally, there is a form of \u201chidden\u201d prostitution, which can involve children as young as 8 years, often in exchange for drugs or some kind of treat or toy. During the day, these children stay in the street often working as street vendors, domestic servants or waitresses. At night they go to dance clubs or sell alcohol in the street. Clients of this type of prostitution are generally adults or adolescents with little money.<ref name=\"unhcr1\"/> \n\nThe problem of child prostitution is exacerbated by poorly enforced laws and by rare and ineffective police raids. However, recently, more efforts have been done to address this problem; in 2008, the police raided several [[brothels]] and rescued  215 children who were working there.<ref name=\"state2\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090621101815/http://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2009/123135.htm Trafficking in Persons Report 2009 Country Narratives \u2013 Countries A Through C]. State.gov. Retrieved on 30 March 2011.</ref> \nThe International Organization for Migration (IOM) and the NGOs Save the Children and Pro-Adolescente conducted public awareness campaigns on the [[trafficking of children]]. La Paz Department and the La Paz city government each operate a shelter for abused and exploited children.\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Bolivia}}\nEconomic and social problems create a climate which is favorable to [[human trafficking]]. Young Bolivian women and girls are trafficked from rural to urban areas for commercial sexual exploitation;<ref name=\"state2\"/> women and children from the indigenous ethnic groups in the [[Altiplano]] region are at greater risk of being [[human trafficking|trafficked]] into prostitution.<ref name=\"state1\"/>\nFaced with extreme poverty, many citizens become economic migrants, and some are victimized by traffickers and forced into prostitution, both inside and outside Bolivia. \n \nThe country is also a source for victims trafficked for sexual exploitation to [[Argentina]], [[Chile]], [[Brazil]], [[Spain]], and the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VG2mDHVSUDcC&pg=PA250&dq=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia#v=onepage&q=Prostitution%20in%20Bolivia&f=false|title=Bolivia Company Laws and Regulations Handbook|first=Usa International Business|last=Publications|date=3 March 2008|publisher=Int'l Business Publications|accessdate=10 January 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9781433069512}}</ref> Weak controls along the borders exacerbate this problem.<ref name=\"state1\"/>\n\nIn 2018 the [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] downgraded Bolivia's rank from 'Tier 2 Watch List' to a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 3]]' country.<ref name=\"state18\">{{cite web |title=Bolivia 2018 Trafficking in Persons Report |url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282616.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726234113/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2018/282616.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 July 2018 |website=U.S. Department of State |accessdate=26 July 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gvnet.com/childprostitution/Bolivia.htm Child Prostitution:The Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children]\n\n{{South America in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution by country|Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Bolivian society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in South America|Bolivia]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChild prostitution:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostitution_in_Bolivia"}
{"title_page": "New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective", "text_new": "__NOTOC__\n[[File:Auckland pride parade 2016 9.jpg|thumb|New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective on Auckland pride parade in 2016]]\nThe '''New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective''' (NZPC) is a [[New Zealand]]-based organisation that supports [[sex workers' rights]] and educates [[prostitution|prostitutes]] about minimizing the risks of the job. It was founded in 1987 and receives funding from the Ministry of Health. One of its founding members was [[Catherine Healy (activist)|Catherine Healy]], who remained NZPC's national coordinator in 2012.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} The funding contract was subsequently managed by the Department of Health, and later, the Ministry of Health, following reorganisation within the Ministry.<ref>Healy, C., Bennachie, C., & Reed, A., (2010) History of the New Zealand Prostitutes Collective; in Abel, G., Fitzgerald, L., & Healy, C., (Eds) ''Taking the crime out of sex work: New Zealand sex workers' fight for decriminalisation'', Bristol: Policy Press</ref>  It has been credited with controlling the spread of [[HIV/AIDS]] in New Zealand.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} It played an active role in the [[New Zealand Labour Party]]-led [[Helen Clark]] administration passing the [[Prostitution Reform Act 2003]], which decriminalised most forms of adult [[prostitution in New Zealand]], despite opposition from the [[Maxim Institute]] and other New Zealand [[Christian Right]] organisations of the time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abel, G., Fitzgerald, L., & Healy, C., (Eds), (2010).  ''Taking the crime out of sex work: New Zealand sex workers' fight for decriminalisation''.  Bristol: Policy Press.\n* Jordan, J (1991) ''Working Girls: Women in the New Zealand Sex Industry talk to Jan Jordan'', Auckland: Penguin\n* [http://www.newint.org/issue252/healthy.htm Catherine Healy and Anna Reed, The Healthy Hooker, The New Internationalist, 252: 16-17, 1994]\n* Chetwynd J. The Prostitutes' Collective: A uniquely New Zealand institution, in ''Intimate Details and Vital Statistics: AIDS, sexuality and the social order in New Zealand''. Auckland University Press 1996\n* Bronwen Lichtenstein, Tradition and experiment in New Zealand AIDS policy, ''AIDS and Public Policy'', 12 (3): 79\u201388, 1997\n* Lichtenstein, B: Reframing \"Eve\" in the AIDS era, in Sex Work and Sex Workers, BM Dank and R Refinetti eds. Transaction, New Brunswick NJ 1998\n* Laverack, G., Whipple, A. 2010. The sirens\u2019 song of empowerment: a case study of health promotion and the New Zealand Prostitutes Collective. Glob Health Prom 17(1) 33\u20138.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nzpc.org.nz}}\n\n{{Prostitution in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:Women's organisations based in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sex worker organizations in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "__NOTOC__\n[[File:Auckland pride parade 2016 9.jpg|thumb|New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective on Auckland pride parade in 2016]]\nThe '''New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective''' (NZPC) is a [[New Zealand]]-based organisation that supports [[sex workers' rights]] and educates [[prostitution|prostitutes]] about minimizing the risks of the job. It was founded in 1987 and receives funding from the Ministry of Health. One of its founding members was [[Catherine Healy (activist)|Catherine Healy]], who remained NZPC's national coordinator in 2012.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} The funding contract was subsequently managed by the Department of Health, and later, the Ministry of Health, following reorganisation within the Ministry.<ref>Healy, C., Bennachie, C., & Reed, A., (2010) History of the New Zealand Prostitutes Collective; in Abel, G., Fitzgerald, L., & Healy, C., (Eds) ''Taking the crime out of sex work: New Zealand sex workers' fight for decriminalisation'', Bristol: Policy Press</ref>  It has been credited with controlling the spread of [[HIV/AIDS]] in New Zealand.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} It played an active role in the [[New Zealand Labour Party]]-led [[Helen Clark]] administration passing the [[Prostitution Reform Act 2003]], which decriminalised most forms of adult [[prostitution in New Zealand]], despite opposition from the [[Maxim Institute]] and other New Zealand [[Christian Right]] organisations of the time.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Abel, G., Fitzgerald, L., & Healy, C., (Eds), (2010).  ''Taking the crime out of sex work: New Zealand sex workers' fight for decriminalisation''.  Bristol: Policy Press.\n* Jordan, J (1991) ''Working Girls: Women in the New Zealand Sex Industry talk to Jan Jordan'', Auckland: Penguin\n* [http://www.newint.org/issue252/healthy.htm Catherine Healy and Anna Reed, The Healthy Hooker, The New Internationalist, 252: 16-17, 1994]\n* Chetwynd J. The Prostitutes' Collective: A uniquely New Zealand institution, in ''Intimate Details and Vital Statistics: AIDS, sexuality and the social order in New Zealand''. Auckland University Press 1996\n* Bronwen Lichtenstein, Tradition and experiment in New Zealand AIDS policy, ''AIDS and Public Policy'', 12 (3): 79-88, 1997\n* Lichtenstein, B: Reframing \"Eve\" in the AIDS era, in Sex Work and Sex Workers, BM Dank and R Refinetti eds. Transaction, New Brunswick NJ 1998\n* Laverack, G., Whipple, A. 2010. The sirens\u2019 song of empowerment: a case study of health promotion and the New Zealand Prostitutes Collective. Glob Health Prom 17(1) 33-8.\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.nzpc.org.nz}}\n\n{{Prostitution in New Zealand}}\n\n[[Category:Women's organisations based in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Sex worker organizations in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 79-88 \u2192 79\u201388 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Zealand_Prostitutes%27_Collective"}
{"title_page": "Catherine Healy (activist)", "text_new": "{{short description|New Zealand activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Dame Catherine Healy \n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|DNZM|size=100%}}\n| image       = Catherine Healy DNZM (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Healy in 2018\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth based on age as of date |61|2017|10|28}}<ref name=\"Stuff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = New Zealander\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = [[Sex workers' rights]] activism\n| occupation  = [[Activist]]\n}}\n\n'''Dame Catherine Alice Healy''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|DNZM}} (born 1955/1956) is a New Zealand [[sex workers' rights]] activist, [[Field research#Fieldwork and Sociology|field researcher]] and former prostitute working for decriminalisation of prostitution and generally for the improvement of the sex work profession. She is the national coordinator and a founding member of the [[New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective]] (NZPC).<ref name=\"Radio New Zealand\">{{cite news | title = Prostitutes Collective disputes trafficking claim | url = http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/79083/prostitutes-collective-disputes-trafficking-claim | newspaper = [[Radio New Zealand]] | date = 4 July 2011 | accessdate = 14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nHealy grew up near [[Eastbourne, New Zealand|Eastbourne]], with three siblings and \"liberal-minded\" parents.<ref name=\"Stuff\"/> As a child she was involved in the anti-apartheid and anti-tour movements, and frequently attended marches and rallies. Her father passed away when she was 15 years old, making her last few years of high school particularly difficult. Healy went on to attend a Teacher's College, and build her early career as a primary school teacher. She now lives with her partner of 30 years in her childhood home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHealy worked as a primary school teacher in Wellington for nine years in the late 1970s and early 1980s. She was first introduced to sex work through her then flatmate, who revealed herself to be a prostitute. Although at first horrified, she once accompanied flatmate on a night out, and eventually took home one her clients. At that time, she decided that sex work was not for her, and continued teaching. Despite this initial disinterest, in 1986 Healy answered an ad to work in a massage parlor to supplement her primary school wages. After a year's absence from teaching, she decided to fully commit to her job as a sex worker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She began working in brothels, namely what is now the General Practitioner bar on Willis St. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/104330042/dame-catherine-healy-brought-in-from-the-cold-after-career-advocating-for-sex-workers|title=Dame Catherine Healy 'brought in from the cold' after career advocating for sex workers|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She reportedly received $2000 a month as a sex worker, compared to her salary of $400 as an educator, which she was able to spend on her frequent trips and adventures abroad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/06/04/616865934/queen-honors-activist-who-fought-to-decriminalize-prostitution|title=Queen Honors Activist Who Fought To Decriminalize Prostitution|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She worked for seven years as a sex worker, until eventually turning her focus towards advocacy for the protection of sex workers and decriminalization of prostitution.  \n\nThe New Zealand Prostitutes Collective was established in 1987 to organize sex workers in this movement for protection and decriminalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Healy and her fellow members of the NZPC initiated this campaign for decriminalisation of prostitution. Prostitution was finally decriminalised in New Zealand in 2003 after the implementation of the [[Prostitution Reform Act 2003]]; Healy was in the public gallery to witness the final vote.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Anderson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/04/new-zealand-former-sex-worker-becomes-a-dame-in-queens-birthday-honours |title=New Zealand former sex worker becomes a dame in Queen's birthday honours |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 June 2018 }}</ref> On 24 February 2010, she was invited by the [[Oxford Union]] at the [[University of Oxford]] to debate whether prostitution should be decriminalised. She became the second New Zealander after [[David Lange]] to be invited to debate at the university. At the university, she argued for decriminalisation of prostitution and won the debate.<ref>{{cite news |title= Kiwi debater convinces Oxford Union on prostitution|author= |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/3371975/Kiwi-debater-convinces-Oxford-Union-on-prostitution |newspaper= [[Stuff.co.nz]]|date= 25 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= NZ prostitutes' advocate speaks at Oxford debate | author = |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10628396 |newspaper= [[The New Zealand Herald]]|date= 25 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nHealy has membership of various boards and committees. She has been invited as a speaker at the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] and acts as an advisory on issues and policy formulations related to prostitution. The Prostitution Law Review Committee, a committee established by the [[New Zealand government]], had Healy as one of its members. She has worked as a [[Field research#Fieldwork and Sociology|field researcher]] and has been involved with multiple research undertakings. She also works as a consultant for prostitutes of all genders, brothel owners and other persons involved in prostitution.<ref name=\"University of Otago\">{{ cite web | url = http://www.otago.ac.nz/anzals/keynotespeakers.html | title = Catherine Healy \u2013 New Zealand Prostitutes Collective | publisher = [[University of Otago]] | accessdate = 14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nWith Gillian Abel and Lisa Fitzgerald, Healy has co-edited the book ''[[Taking the Crime Out of Sex Work: New Zealand Sex Workers' Fight for Decriminalisation]]''.<ref name=\"University of Otago\"/> The book argues decriminalization has resulted in better working conditions for prostitutes.<ref>{{cite news |title= Decriminalisation of sex industry positive move|author= |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1005/S00110.htm|newspaper= Scoop|date= |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> She lives in Eastbourne.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|last=Romanos|first=Joseph|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/archive/the-wellingtonian/3501279/The-Wellingtonian-interview-Catherine-Healy|title=The Wellingtonian interview: Catherine Healy|date=|newspaper=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=14 April 2012|authorlink=Joseph Romanos}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2018, Catherine Healy was awarded a New Zealand Order of Merit by Queen Elizabeth II on her official birthday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44354829|title=NZ sex work activist becomes a dame|date=4 June 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=9 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> This award recognized her nearly 30-year career dedicated to decriminalizing sex work. This high honor was approved by the Queen, in accordance with the advice of the prime minister. She was one of eight people awarded this special accolade in 2018, totaling five new dames and three new knights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/06/04/616865934/queen-honors-activist-who-fought-to-decriminalize-prostitution|title=Queen Honors Activist Who Fought To Decriminalize Prostitution|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHealy was awarded the [[New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/qb2018-dnzm |title=Queen's Birthday honours 2018 \u2013 citations for Dames Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit |date=4 June 2018 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]], she was appointed a [[Dame Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to the rights of sex workers.<ref name=Guardian/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/queens-birthday-honours-list-2018 |title=Queen's Birthday honours list 2018 |date=4 June 2018 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Prostitution in New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Prostitution in New Zealand|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Healy, Catherine}}\n[[Category:New Zealand prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand activists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women activists]]\n[[Category:Sex positivism]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dames Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal 1993]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Hutt]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|New Zealand activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Dame Catherine Healy \n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|DNZM|size=100%}}\n| image       = Catherine Healy DNZM (cropped).jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Healy in 2018\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{birth based on age as of date |61|2017|10|28}}<ref name=\"Stuff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n| birth_place = New Zealand\n| death_date  = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| nationality = New Zealander\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = [[Sex workers' rights]] activism\n| occupation  = [[Activist]]\n}}\n\n'''Dame Catherine Alice Healy''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|DNZM}} (born 1955/1956) is a New Zealand [[sex workers' rights]] activist, [[Field research#Fieldwork and Sociology|field researcher]] and former prostitute working for decriminalisation of prostitution and generally for the improvement of the sex work profession. She is the national coordinator and a founding member of the [[New Zealand Prostitutes' Collective]] (NZPC).<ref name=\"Radio New Zealand\">{{cite news | title = Prostitutes Collective disputes trafficking claim | url = http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/79083/prostitutes-collective-disputes-trafficking-claim | newspaper = [[Radio New Zealand]] | date = 4 July 2011 | accessdate = 14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nHealy grew up near [[Eastbourne, New Zealand|Eastbourne]], with three siblings and \"liberal-minded\" parents.<ref name=\"Stuff\"/> As a child she was involved in the anti-apartheid and anti-tour movements, and frequently attended marches and rallies. Her father passed away when she was 15 years old, making her last few years of high school particularly difficult. Healy went on to attend a Teacher's College, and build her early career as a primary school teacher. She now lives with her partner of 30 years in her childhood home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHealy worked as a primary school teacher in Wellington for nine years in the late 1970's and early 1980's. She was first introduced to sex work through her then flatmate, who revealed herself to be a prostitute. Although at first horrified, she once accompanied flatmate on a night out, and eventually took home one her clients. At that time, she decided that sex work was not for her, and continued teaching. Despite this initial disinterest, in 1986 Healy answered an ad to work in a massage parlor to supplement her primary school wages. After a year's absence from teaching, she decided to fully commit to her job as a sex worker.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She began working in brothels, namely what is now the General Practitioner bar on Willis St. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/104330042/dame-catherine-healy-brought-in-from-the-cold-after-career-advocating-for-sex-workers|title=Dame Catherine Healy 'brought in from the cold' after career advocating for sex workers|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She reportedly received $2000 a month as a sex worker, compared to her salary of $400 as an educator, which she was able to spend on her frequent trips and adventures abroad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/06/04/616865934/queen-honors-activist-who-fought-to-decriminalize-prostitution|title=Queen Honors Activist Who Fought To Decriminalize Prostitution|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> She worked for seven years as a sex worker, until eventually turning her focus towards advocacy for the protection of sex workers and decriminalization of prostitution.  \n\nThe New Zealand Prostitutes Collective was established in 1987 to organize sex workers in this movement for protection and decriminalization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/98216198/national-portrait-catherine-healy--the-exponent|title=National Portrait: Catherine Healy \u2013 The Exponent|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Healy and her fellow members of the NZPC initiated this campaign for decriminalisation of prostitution. Prostitution was finally decriminalised in New Zealand in 2003 after the implementation of the [[Prostitution Reform Act 2003]]; Healy was in the public gallery to witness the final vote.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Anderson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jun/04/new-zealand-former-sex-worker-becomes-a-dame-in-queens-birthday-honours |title=New Zealand former sex worker becomes a dame in Queen's birthday honours |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 June 2018 }}</ref> On 24 February 2010, she was invited by the [[Oxford Union]] at the [[University of Oxford]] to debate whether prostitution should be decriminalised. She became the second New Zealander after [[David Lange]] to be invited to debate at the university. At the university, she argued for decriminalisation of prostitution and won the debate.<ref>{{cite news |title= Kiwi debater convinces Oxford Union on prostitution|author= |url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/3371975/Kiwi-debater-convinces-Oxford-Union-on-prostitution |newspaper= [[Stuff.co.nz]]|date= 25 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= NZ prostitutes' advocate speaks at Oxford debate | author = |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10628396 |newspaper= [[The New Zealand Herald]]|date= 25 February 2010|accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nHealy has membership of various boards and committees. She has been invited as a speaker at the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]] and acts as an advisory on issues and policy formulations related to prostitution. The Prostitution Law Review Committee, a committee established by the [[New Zealand government]], had Healy as one of its members. She has worked as a [[Field research#Fieldwork and Sociology|field researcher]] and has been involved with multiple research undertakings. She also works as a consultant for prostitutes of all genders, brothel owners and other persons involved in prostitution.<ref name=\"University of Otago\">{{ cite web | url = http://www.otago.ac.nz/anzals/keynotespeakers.html | title = Catherine Healy \u2013 New Zealand Prostitutes Collective | publisher = [[University of Otago]] | accessdate = 14 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nWith Gillian Abel and Lisa Fitzgerald, Healy has co-edited the book ''[[Taking the Crime Out of Sex Work: New Zealand Sex Workers' Fight for Decriminalisation]]''.<ref name=\"University of Otago\"/> The book argues decriminalization has resulted in better working conditions for prostitutes.<ref>{{cite news |title= Decriminalisation of sex industry positive move|author= |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1005/S00110.htm|newspaper= Scoop|date= |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> She lives in Eastbourne.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|last=Romanos|first=Joseph|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/archive/the-wellingtonian/3501279/The-Wellingtonian-interview-Catherine-Healy|title=The Wellingtonian interview: Catherine Healy|date=|newspaper=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|accessdate=14 April 2012|authorlink=Joseph Romanos}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2018, Catherine Healy was awarded a New Zealand Order of Merit by Queen Elizabeth II on her official birthday.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44354829|title=NZ sex work activist becomes a dame|date=4 June 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=9 March 2020|language=en-GB}}</ref> This award recognized her nearly 30 year career dedicated to decriminalizing sex work. This high honor was approved by the Queen, in accordance with the advice of the prime minister. She was one of eight people awarded this special accolade in 2018, totaling five new dames and three new knights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2018/06/04/616865934/queen-honors-activist-who-fought-to-decriminalize-prostitution|title=Queen Honors Activist Who Fought To Decriminalize Prostitution|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nHealy was awarded the [[New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/qb2018-dnzm |title=Queen's Birthday honours 2018 \u2013 citations for Dames Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit |date=4 June 2018 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 Birthday Honours (New Zealand)|2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]], she was appointed a [[Dame Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to the rights of sex workers.<ref name=Guardian/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/publications/queens-birthday-honours-list-2018 |title=Queen's Birthday honours list 2018 |date=4 June 2018 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Prostitution in New Zealand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Prostitution in New Zealand|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Healy, Catherine}}\n[[Category:New Zealand prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand activists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women activists]]\n[[Category:Sex positivism]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dames Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal 1993]]\n[[Category:1950s births]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Hutt]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 30 year \u2192 30-year, 1970's and early 1980's \u2192 1970s and early 1980s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catherine_Healy_(activist)"}
